        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This is a continuum experiment so all the basebands have the maximum bandwidth. However, baseband 3 includes the CO 3-2 line and has a channel width to 1.7km/s. Although observing the CO line is not the main driver of the propsal, the detection of molecular gas associated with the ring will be very important, since from the kinematics we would be able to derive a kinematical timescale of the ring. In addition it would be used to discard a dust detection not related with the mid-IR dust (e.g. a circumstellar envelope from an evolved star). The sensitivity for the CO 3-2 line is 15 mK for a spectral resolution of 1km/s, which provides a column density sensitivity at 5-sigma of roughly ~1e20cm-2.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This is a detection experiment so request an angular resolution large enough to avoid resolving too much the emission. About 1 arcsec should be safe enough, since the brightest spot appear relatively compact in the Spitzer image.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The flux measured at 24mum (micrometers) by Wachter et al. (2008) over a narrow elliptical aperture in the 24mum Spitzer image is about 1.2 Jy. However, the ring is not uniform, and the emission is dominated by few bright clumps. We have selected a region around the strongest 24mum emission, located in the Southern part of the ring and that is not contaminated from emission arising from red giants (Wachter et al. 2008). The selected region alsoinclude a second bright dust peak from the ring. From the Spitzer 24mum we estimate that the brightest clump has about 1/5 of the total flux in the ring. In order to extrapolate the expected flux at 870mum we adopt a temperature of 80 K (Wachter et al. 2008). For 24mum and 870mum  we have also adopted the dust opacity computed by Ossenkopf and Henning (1994) at these wavelengths for dust particle without ices and for a density of 1e6 cm-3. Under these conditions, we expect that the brightest clump from the ring has a 870mum flux density of about 0.15mJy. We request a sensitivity of 23muJy/Beam to assure the detection (signal-to-noise ratio of 7). Note, that if the dust emission is a bit cooler, then the dust 870mum flux density will be higher. See also the correlator set-up.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
