    <prp:abstract>Magnetars are a small class of strongly magnetized pulsars (B~10^{14}-10^{15} G) emitting extremely powerful X/gamma-ray flares on several timescales. Magnetars' giant flares second in energetics, in our Galaxy, only supernova explosions: an energy of ~10^{45}-10^{47} erg is emitted in a few minutes. An infrared elliptical ring has been discovered by Spitzer surrounding the magnetar SGR 1900+14, one of the three objects that ever showed a giant flare (occurred on August 27th, 1998), and which is hosted by a massive star cluster. The most probable interpretation for this ring is a dust-free cavity produced in the magnetar environment by the giant flare via different dust destruction processes, embedded in a hot dust cloud illuminated continuously by close-by massive stars. We ask for 8.2 hours of ALMA observation at 345 GHz to image the brightest part of this unique dust ring, study its shape in the mm-band, and model its spectral energy distribution. These observations will reveal the true origin of the elliptical ring, and have the potential to infer for the first time the energetic in the UV and soft X-ray band, and the anisotropy of a magnetar giant flare.</prp:abstract>
